<subSubSection pageId="33" pageNumber="34" type="notes">
<paragraph pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Notes.</paragraph>
<paragraph pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
This genus, with about ten species known to occur in Madagascar, was transferred from the subfamily 
<taxonomicName lsidName="" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Galerucinae">Galerucinae</taxonomicName>
to the 
<taxonomicName lsidName="" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" rank="subFamily" subFamily="Alticinae">Alticinae</taxonomicName>
(currently the tribe 
<taxonomicName lsidName="" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" rank="tribe" tribe="Alticini">Alticini</taxonomicName>
) by 
<bibRefCitation pageId="33" pageNumber="34">
Biondi and 
<normalizedToken originalValue="D’Alessandro">D'Alessandro</normalizedToken>
(2010a)
</bibRefCitation>
. The reason being the presence of a metafemoral spring, very similar to that described for the Oriental genus 
<taxonomicName authority="Duvivier, 1892" authorityName="Duvivier" authorityYear="1892" class="Insecta" family="Chrysomelidae" genus="Mandarella" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Mandarella" order="Coleoptera" pageId="33" pageNumber="34" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">Mandarella</taxonomicName>
Duvivier (1892b: 433) (cf. 
<bibRefCitation pageId="33" pageNumber="34">Furth and Suzuki 1994</bibRefCitation>
).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
